04:23.378 --> 04:24.277
(school bell ringing)

04:24.329 --> 04:26.079
I'm sorry, I...

04:26.131 --> 04:28.832
I don't think I understand
what you just told me.

04:28.917 --> 04:31.235
I said, I'm making
swim coach Roz Washington

04:31.302 --> 04:33.453
co-coach of the Cheerios!

04:33.505 --> 04:36.640
How can you do this to me?

04:36.724 --> 04:38.275
ROZ:
I think I can answer
that question.

04:38.343 --> 04:41.478
This Saturday the Cheerios!
had Regionals tournament.

04:41.563 --> 04:44.348
You were 15 minutes late.
That's unacceptable.

04:44.432 --> 04:46.016
I had a doctor's appointment.

04:46.100 --> 04:48.018
Oh... I know.
The doctor had to shine

04:48.102 --> 04:51.688
a flashlight in your va-jay-jay
to get all the bats to fly out.

04:51.773 --> 04:53.941
I understand that keeping
bats out of your womb

04:53.992 --> 04:57.110
is an important part of having a
baby when you're older than God.

04:57.162 --> 05:01.281
But it is no way to win
a national championship.
Sue...

05:01.332 --> 05:03.801
The lovely and talented
bronze medalist

05:03.868 --> 05:05.586
Roz Washington has a point.

05:05.653 --> 05:08.672
We need the money
and sponsorships that only

05:08.756 --> 05:10.457
a national championship
can bring to the school,

05:10.508 --> 05:13.794
and your condition is
compromising your work.

05:13.845 --> 05:15.262
It's settled.
My word is law.

05:15.329 --> 05:17.681
This will not stand!

05:17.765 --> 05:18.882
Oh, it's gonna stand.

05:18.967 --> 05:20.333
And you know what else
is gonna stand?

05:20.385 --> 05:23.554
Your fully-grown, adult baby

05:23.638 --> 05:26.523
when he pops out of your birth
canal, before he hurries off

05:26.608 --> 05:29.109
to the high-powered law firm
where he has just made partner.

05:29.176 --> 05:32.362
So take your Centrum Silver,
and your old ass,

05:32.447 --> 05:35.315
and find a new dream.

05:42.857 --> 05:45.692
What if I can guarantee you
a national championship?

05:45.743 --> 05:47.127
And how will you do that?

05:47.194 --> 05:49.246
The Glee Club.
If they win at Nationals,

05:49.330 --> 05:51.882
the school wins
a $10,000 cash prize.

05:51.950 --> 05:54.001
I get you that money,

05:54.052 --> 05:57.671
I get to run the cheerleading
program alone!

05:57.722 --> 06:00.173
(whistle blows)
Five, six, seven, eight!

06:00.225 --> 06:01.091
♪

06:07.348 --> 06:09.600
Stop! Please, stop!

06:09.684 --> 06:12.052
This is an embarrassment.

06:12.103 --> 06:14.171
Hey, Mercedes.
Who you texting?

06:14.239 --> 06:15.689
I'm not texting anyone,

06:15.740 --> 06:18.025
I'm donating to
the Obama campaign...

06:18.076 --> 06:20.110
(screams)
My Droid!

06:20.194 --> 06:22.613
Good news! I booked a tour at
the Railroad Museum on Friday,

06:22.697 --> 06:25.365
which means we're gonna have
an awesome Senior's Ditch Day.

06:25.416 --> 06:26.950
What is she doing here?
Hey, Granny Panties!

06:27.035 --> 06:28.619
I'm taking over Booty Camp1

06:28.703 --> 06:30.236
Why on earth do you
want to run Booty Camp?

06:30.288 --> 06:32.372
Because, as I established, I
want to help you win Nationals.

06:32.423 --> 06:34.708
And I am a champion
who can whip that squad

06:34.759 --> 06:36.126
of pear-shaped teens into shape.

06:36.210 --> 06:38.211
You're out of shape,
you're constantly late,

06:38.263 --> 06:39.630
and when you're not
too busy texting,

06:39.714 --> 06:40.931
you're complaining about

06:41.015 --> 06:42.849
the choreography
you're too lazy to learn.

06:42.917 --> 06:45.602
You're nothing but
a coven of tardy,

06:45.687 --> 06:48.272
narcissistic, bloated
bags of cellulite

06:48.356 --> 06:49.940
who will stab each other
in the back

06:50.024 --> 06:51.525
at the first glimpse of a solo

06:51.592 --> 06:54.811
in a competition hosted by
a late-night horror movie host.

06:54.896 --> 06:56.763
Well, those days are over.

06:56.814 --> 06:58.065
(school bell ringing)
Sue?

06:58.116 --> 06:59.533
We need to talk about what
happened at Booty Camp.

06:59.600 --> 07:02.435
Oh, you mean my epic smack down
of the glee club over their

07:02.487 --> 07:04.538
complete apathy and
lack of professionalism?

07:04.605 --> 07:06.540
According to the kids,
you were typical abusive

07:06.607 --> 07:08.292
belligerent self,
only more so.

07:08.376 --> 07:10.327
I just got this
e-mail from Kurt.

07:10.411 --> 07:12.412
"Mr. Shue, save us!

07:12.463 --> 07:14.715
Coach Sue is meaner
than Tabatha!"
First of all,

07:14.782 --> 07:17.217
I have absolutely no idea who
Porcelain is referring to.

07:17.284 --> 07:19.219
I'm assuming it's gay and niche.

07:19.286 --> 07:20.804
Secondly, based on
the pathetic display

07:20.888 --> 07:22.622
I just saw?

07:22.674 --> 07:25.559
Your glee club's back-to-back
victories were flukes.

07:25.626 --> 07:26.727
Oh...
Against Vocal Adrenaline?

07:26.794 --> 07:28.679
On the national stage?

07:28.763 --> 07:30.296
You'll be like lambs
to the slaughter.

07:30.348 --> 07:33.183
Why are you resisting
my help, William?

07:33.267 --> 07:35.235
We should try to
inspire and encourage

07:35.302 --> 07:37.303
our kids, Sue,
not humiliate and crush them.

07:37.355 --> 07:38.638
I don't get it.

07:38.690 --> 07:40.691
You were acting like you
had turned over a new leaf.

07:40.775 --> 07:42.609
William... I'm near the end
of my first trimester.

07:42.660 --> 07:45.278
I'm wildly hormonal, riding out

07:45.330 --> 07:47.480
massive, unpredictable
mood swings.

07:47.532 --> 07:50.000
Stop trying to
understand my actions.

07:50.084 --> 07:52.152
Maybe you should
talk to your doctor

07:52.203 --> 07:54.171
about adjusting your medication?
Oh, I'll ask.

07:54.255 --> 07:56.590
I'm going there this week to
confirm the sex of my daughter.

07:56.657 --> 07:59.626
Mm! Oh, Sue!
That's a mother-to-be

07:59.677 --> 08:01.845
single most important doctor
visit. Who's going with you?

08:01.929 --> 08:03.513
Same person who's going to
help me raise this child,

08:03.598 --> 08:04.998
Barbara Gordon. No one.

08:05.049 --> 08:08.802
We'll...
Sue, you can't go alone.

08:08.853 --> 08:11.004
No, you need a friend there,
for moral support.

08:11.055 --> 08:12.639
I agree.

08:14.475 --> 08:16.643
We'll go with you.

08:18.012 --> 08:18.895
(school bell ringing)

08:18.980 --> 08:20.346
You okay?

08:20.398 --> 08:21.498
You seem a little preoccupied.

08:21.566 --> 08:22.866
Oh, well, my brother's in town.

08:22.950 --> 08:25.018
He's picking me up,
taking me out to lunch.

08:25.069 --> 08:26.519
Blaine, that's exciting!

08:26.571 --> 08:28.789
I finally get to meet this
mysterious brother of yours,

08:28.856 --> 08:30.123
who you refuse to talk about.

08:30.191 --> 08:31.708
I'm dying to know
what he looks like.

08:31.793 --> 08:33.543
Oh, trust me, you...

08:33.628 --> 08:34.910
you already know
what he looks like.

08:34.996 --> 08:36.496
Blainie!

08:36.547 --> 08:37.664
Hey, Coop!
Hey!

08:37.715 --> 08:39.416
Hey.
How are you, bud?

08:39.500 --> 08:40.801
Good. Good to see you, man.

08:40.868 --> 08:41.868
This your,
this your boyfriend, here?

08:41.919 --> 08:43.220
Actually, yes, it is.
Hi.

08:43.304 --> 08:45.338
Kurt, this is my brother...
Nice to meet you.

08:45.390 --> 08:47.391
...Cooper Anderson.
Oh, my God.
You're the guy from

08:47.475 --> 08:48.558
the freecreditratingtoday.com
commercials!

08:48.643 --> 08:49.843
Guilty as charged.

08:49.894 --> 08:51.261
♪ Know your score

08:51.345 --> 08:54.014
♪ Freecreditratingtoday.com

08:54.065 --> 08:56.016
♪ Slash savings!

08:56.067 --> 09:00.487
I love those commercials!
The jingle's my ringtone!

09:00.554 --> 09:01.988
Excuse me, I'm sorry
to interrupt, but, um,

09:02.056 --> 09:03.490
I just needed to tell you

09:03.557 --> 09:05.909
that I am an enormous
fan of your work.

09:05.993 --> 09:06.993
Thank you.

09:07.061 --> 09:08.829
Will you sign my breast?
My pleasure.

09:09.864 --> 09:11.731
"Keep on dreaming.

09:11.783 --> 09:13.500
"Yours...
Mine.

09:13.567 --> 09:16.402
Cooper Anderson."

09:16.454 --> 09:18.004
You do me a great honor.

09:18.072 --> 09:20.590
And if Alan Menken isn't
personally writing you

09:20.675 --> 09:22.542
a fairy tale musical
at this very moment,

09:22.593 --> 09:25.178
I will hunt him down
and beat him senseless

09:25.246 --> 09:26.463
with a cudgel.
(laughs)

09:26.547 --> 09:31.101
Because you, sir,
are a Disney prince.

09:31.185 --> 09:33.019
Wow.

09:33.087 --> 09:36.356
God, it is great to be
back in the Midwest.

09:36.423 --> 09:38.608
My commercial's on hiatus,

09:38.693 --> 09:41.261
so I told my agent I was
headed back to the heartland

09:41.312 --> 09:43.947
to press the flesh,
do some character research.

09:44.031 --> 09:46.566
Next season's commercials have
a lot more intense, gritty

09:46.617 --> 09:48.201
character stuff, so
I really want to explore

09:48.269 --> 09:50.070
my salt-of-the-earth roots.

09:50.121 --> 09:51.938
Blaine, your brother's
the best-looking man
in North America.

09:51.989 --> 09:53.790
Um, Coop and I are gonna head...
Excuse me.

09:53.875 --> 09:55.876
Gaston, if I could pull you
away from these ladies

09:55.943 --> 09:58.962
for just a moment; I have
something I'd like to ask you.

09:59.046 --> 10:01.581
Yeah. I mean, that's...

10:01.632 --> 10:04.384
that's why I never really
talk about my brother.

10:04.719 --> 10:04.719
+

10:06.753 --> 10:08.421
PUCK:
We all know why we're here.
I've waited five years for this.

10:08.472 --> 10:09.722
I want ideas for
Senior Ditch Day. Go.

10:09.789 --> 10:11.424
Ooh! A Gershwin/Sondheim
scavenger hunt!

10:11.475 --> 10:12.675
That sounds like torture.

10:12.759 --> 10:14.427
We want actual ideas, Kurt.

10:14.478 --> 10:15.895
<i>How about a dance movie
marathon? Footloose...</i>

10:15.962 --> 10:17.763
<i>Footloose 2011.</i>

10:17.814 --> 10:19.398
What about a non-alcoholic
pub crawl?

10:19.466 --> 10:21.400
It's Senior Ditch Day, not
Senior Citizen's Ditch Day.

10:21.468 --> 10:23.853
It's springtime. I would like
to see something give birth.

10:23.937 --> 10:25.538
(giggling)

10:25.606 --> 10:27.857
Quinn, I'm so sorry.

10:27.925 --> 10:30.993
It was my wedding
that you were going to

10:31.078 --> 10:32.995
when you got into
your car crash, and...

10:33.080 --> 10:34.580
you were answering
my text message, and now...

10:34.648 --> 10:36.165
we're all sitting here,
and we're talking about

10:36.250 --> 10:38.251
this day that's supposed to be

10:38.318 --> 10:40.086
the most amazing
and unforgettable day

10:40.153 --> 10:42.088
of our high school lives,
and we're-we're completely

10:42.155 --> 10:44.640
ignoring the fact that
she's sitting in that chair?

10:44.708 --> 10:47.510
It's not right.

10:47.594 --> 10:49.779
It's not right,
and it shouldn't be like this.

10:49.846 --> 10:51.631
Well, maybe not, but...

10:51.682 --> 10:53.549
this is the way it is.

10:53.634 --> 10:56.769
My accident, which you did
not cause, by the way,

10:56.836 --> 11:00.223
does not define me
or ruin our senior year.

11:00.307 --> 11:02.642
I meant what I said
in the choir room.

11:02.693 --> 11:05.311
I'm not gonna dwell on this, and
neither should any of you, okay?

11:05.362 --> 11:06.395
Come here.

11:12.786 --> 11:16.606
Come on.
(chuckles) Come on.

11:18.909 --> 11:21.244
Now, we are ditching as planned.

11:22.546 --> 11:24.914
I think we should go
to Six Flags.

11:24.998 --> 11:27.032
The Lady Fabray has chosen
wisely. Six Flags it is.

11:27.084 --> 11:28.200
Meeting adjourned.

11:28.252 --> 11:29.552
Hey!

11:29.636 --> 11:31.537
Hey, Finn, can you hang back
for a sec?

11:31.588 --> 11:32.922
The Apple guy.

11:33.006 --> 11:35.057
The Facebook guy.
Abraham Lincoln.

11:35.142 --> 11:36.809
What do these guys all have
in common with us?

11:36.876 --> 11:38.711
I don't know.
They were all in a show choir?

11:38.762 --> 11:41.147
None of 'em were
taken seriously in
high school, dude.

11:41.214 --> 11:42.715
They were written off
by the world

11:42.766 --> 11:44.150
until they got
the big idea.

11:44.217 --> 11:45.985
Then bingo!
The rest is history.

11:46.052 --> 11:47.520
Okay. So what's your big idea?

11:47.571 --> 11:51.357
Lima's only got 22 pools.

11:51.408 --> 11:53.242
Southern California has
800 freaking thousand!

11:53.327 --> 11:54.560
I Googled it.

11:54.611 --> 11:57.697
So after graduation,
I'm gonna move to L.A.

11:57.748 --> 11:59.565
and expand my
pool cleaning business.

11:59.616 --> 12:01.367
And I want you to be
my business partner.

12:01.418 --> 12:02.868
With your brains
and my jaw line,

12:02.919 --> 12:04.403
I'm telling you,
we'd kill it.

12:04.454 --> 12:07.173
Wow, dude, I'm so honored
that you'd even consider me.

12:07.240 --> 12:08.574
But you know, after we graduate,

12:08.625 --> 12:10.259
I'm going to New York
with Rachel.

12:10.344 --> 12:13.713
Okay. Let's say you weren't,
just 'cause maybe she doesn't

12:13.764 --> 12:16.599
get into that fancy school
or you don't get married
right away.

12:16.683 --> 12:18.384
We are. It's gonna happen.

12:18.435 --> 12:19.418
Okay.

12:19.469 --> 12:21.721
But, hey, could
you do me a favor?

12:21.772 --> 12:23.589
Um, you know that
blonde on Sycamore Street

12:23.640 --> 12:25.608
that likes to mow
her lawn in tube tops?

12:25.692 --> 12:26.925
Yeah, Mrs. Tennison.
Yeah.

12:26.977 --> 12:28.260
Well, her Jacuzzi's busted.

12:28.312 --> 12:30.396
So, I thought since you know
so much about motors,

12:30.447 --> 12:32.481
you could take a look at it.
Help me out.

12:32.566 --> 12:34.950
Yeah. All right,
I could probably do that.

12:35.035 --> 12:36.485
(bell ringing)

12:36.570 --> 12:41.073
Lazy idiots, your leader
Will Schuester has informed me

12:41.124 --> 12:43.743
that my teaching methods
are harsh and too extreme.

12:43.794 --> 12:47.013
So I've decided to show you
what a real artist looks

12:47.080 --> 12:48.714
and acts like.

12:48.782 --> 12:52.918
Ladies and gays,
as my gift to you,

12:52.969 --> 12:54.637
which you do not deserve,

12:54.721 --> 12:57.306
I give you
Porcelain's famous brother...

12:57.391 --> 12:58.391
Actually, it's my brother.

12:58.458 --> 12:59.809
...Cooper Anderson.

13:02.062 --> 13:03.062
Thank you, Sue.

13:05.232 --> 13:06.982
Namaste.
Okay.

13:07.067 --> 13:10.019
Guys, it was just a few years
ago that I was sitting

13:10.103 --> 13:13.489
in a sad drab room like this
with dreams like yours

13:13.573 --> 13:16.308
that I thought would
never come true.

13:16.360 --> 13:18.477
But you know what?
They did.

13:18.528 --> 13:22.531
So, tomorrow, at Sue's
insistence, I will be teaching

13:22.616 --> 13:25.201
a Master class in acting
for anyone who's interested

13:25.285 --> 13:27.319
in becoming successful
in the business like me.

13:27.371 --> 13:28.587
Fantastic!

13:30.924 --> 13:32.324
Cooper, we can't
thank you enough.

13:32.376 --> 13:35.127
This is so generous of you to
share your time and expertise.

13:35.178 --> 13:37.763
Well, it's very clear that
the Anderson brothers
are very talented,

13:37.831 --> 13:40.499
and I'm sure that there were
many a family holiday

13:40.550 --> 13:42.885
where the two of you
maybe did a little duet
by the piano?

13:42.969 --> 13:45.838
Actually, it's funny that you
should mention that because

13:45.889 --> 13:47.506
Blaine and I were famous
around the neighborhood.

13:47.557 --> 13:48.841
Not famous.

13:48.892 --> 13:51.677
We were pretty famous
around the neighborhood

13:51.728 --> 13:52.978
for our dueling
Simon LeBon impressions.

13:53.029 --> 13:56.148
Oh, no, no, no, no.
Please don't make me do that.

13:56.199 --> 13:57.283
Oh, no, Blaine,
you have to.

13:57.350 --> 13:58.401
You're both so
handsome and good.

13:58.485 --> 14:00.236
Come on, Blaine.
What do you say?

14:00.320 --> 14:02.321
How about a little Duran Duran?
Is that okay?

14:02.372 --> 14:03.956
Yeah.
Come on.

14:04.023 --> 14:05.825
Okay, okay, okay.

14:07.193 --> 14:08.994
You're on, Cooper.

14:09.045 --> 14:10.713
Ooh, the cardigan's
coming off.
Whoo!

14:10.797 --> 14:14.250
(Duran Duran's
"Hungry Like the Wolf" begins)

14:14.334 --> 14:17.336
♪ Darken the city,
night is a wire ♪

14:17.387 --> 14:21.140
♪ Steam in the subway,
Earth is afire ♪

14:21.207 --> 14:25.878
♪ Do, do, do-do-do, do-do-do
do-do-do, do-do-do, do, do ♪

14:28.381 --> 14:32.768
♪ Woman, you want me,
give me a sign ♪

14:32.853 --> 14:34.987
♪ And catch my breathing
even closer behind ♪

14:35.054 --> 14:40.576
♪ Do, do, do-do-do, do-do-do
do-do-do, do-do-do, do, do ♪

14:40.660 --> 14:42.945
(Duran Duran's "Rio" begins)

14:43.029 --> 14:48.951
♪ Her name is Rio and she dances
on the sand ♪

14:49.035 --> 14:51.036
<i>♪ Smell like I sound ♪</i>

14:51.087 --> 14:55.508
♪ Just like that river twisting
through a dusty land ♪

14:55.575 --> 14:57.242
<i>♪ Straddle the line ♪</i>

14:57.294 --> 15:03.632
♪ And when she shines, she
really shows you all she can ♪

15:03.717 --> 15:05.301
<i>♪ Mouth is alive ♪</i>

15:05.385 --> 15:10.756
♪ Oh, Rio, oh, Rio, dance
across the Rio Grande ♪

15:14.311 --> 15:16.145
♪ Hungry like the wolf

15:18.598 --> 15:21.283
♪ Hungry like the wolf

15:21.368 --> 15:24.453
(distorted voice):
♪ Hungry like the wolf

15:24.538 --> 15:26.038
<i>♪ Don't make a sound ♪</i>

15:26.105 --> 15:32.110
♪ Her name is Rio,
she don't need to understand ♪

15:32.162 --> 15:33.712
<i>♪ Yeah
♪ Smell like I sound ♪</i>

15:33.780 --> 15:39.218
♪ And I might find her
if I'm looking like I can ♪

15:39.285 --> 15:40.803
<i>♪ Straddle the line ♪</i>

15:40.887 --> 15:46.475
♪ Oh, Rio, oh, Rio, hear them
shout across the land ♪

15:46.560 --> 15:48.093
♪ Mouth is alive

15:48.144 --> 15:52.932
♪ From mountains in the north
down to the Rio Grande ♪

15:52.983 --> 15:55.651
<i>♪ Burning the ground ♪</i>

15:55.735 --> 15:59.972
♪ Her name is Rio,
she don't need to understand ♪

16:00.023 --> 16:01.740
<i>♪ Smell like I sound ♪</i>

16:01.808 --> 16:07.696
♪ From mountains in the north,
down to the Rio Grande ♪

16:07.781 --> 16:09.198
♪ Burning the ground.

16:09.282 --> 16:10.583
(cheering)

16:10.650 --> 16:12.484
(applause)

16:14.120 --> 16:17.206
Standing O. Whoo!
Well...

16:17.290 --> 16:20.158
I was really great
in that number.

16:20.210 --> 16:21.660
(bell ringing)

16:23.143 --> 16:23.143
+

16:24.156 --> 16:25.439
Could I get
a wee bit of cheese with that?

16:25.524 --> 16:26.907
What part of Scotland
are you from?

16:26.992 --> 16:29.026
Ireland. We're the micks,
they're the macs.

16:29.077 --> 16:30.411
I'll get you guys
some free Cokes.

16:30.495 --> 16:31.529
Oh, cheers.

16:31.580 --> 16:33.897
Bless you.
Why do you do that?

16:33.949 --> 16:36.951
Service industry is a great
place to try out new accents.

16:37.035 --> 16:38.169
Keeps your instrument
from getting rusty.

16:38.236 --> 16:39.870
Use everything.

16:39.921 --> 16:41.339
Will do.

16:41.406 --> 16:44.208
So, nice job on
the song today.
Really nice.

16:44.259 --> 16:47.294
Oh, thank you.
You were a little
pitchy on "Rio,"

16:47.379 --> 16:49.296
and your moves lacked a theme,
though.

16:49.381 --> 16:53.050
My theme was dancing,
I guess.
But you have to give in to it.

16:53.101 --> 16:54.552
Stanislavsky says,

16:54.603 --> 16:56.721
"The fingers are the eyes
of the body,"

16:56.772 --> 17:00.191
but he never mentioned
that the toes are the ears.

17:00.258 --> 17:01.642
You're unbelievable.

17:01.727 --> 17:03.927
What do you mean?
What are you doing?
What?

17:03.979 --> 17:07.064
All you ever do is tell me
what I'm doing wrong.

17:07.115 --> 17:08.949
You waste no opportunity
to remind me

17:09.034 --> 17:11.117
how much I suck
at, like, everything.

17:11.203 --> 17:13.788
(Hanson's "MMMBop" playing)
No, no. Come on, Blaine.

17:13.872 --> 17:15.105
Your balance is
completely off.

17:15.156 --> 17:18.659
I just learned to walk
three years ago.

17:18.743 --> 17:21.412
If that happened, I'm so sorry.

17:21.463 --> 17:23.164
But I don't,
I don't remember it.

17:23.248 --> 17:24.248
Of course you don't.

17:24.299 --> 17:26.300
Hey, hey, little brother,

17:26.385 --> 17:29.086
I know there is an age
difference between us,

17:29.137 --> 17:31.288
But I'd really want
to be closer to you.

17:31.356 --> 17:33.724
I want to get to know you
a little better,

17:33.792 --> 17:35.926
all right?

17:35.977 --> 17:37.428
That's why I'm here.

17:37.479 --> 17:40.347
Yeah. No, I would love that.
I'd like that.

17:40.432 --> 17:41.632
Great! So you're gonna come

17:41.683 --> 17:43.100
to my Master class tomorrow,
right?

17:43.151 --> 17:44.735
<i>Right?
Yeah, sure.</i>

17:44.803 --> 17:46.270
Great. Cheers.

17:46.321 --> 17:47.605
The accent.

17:47.656 --> 17:48.739
Top o' the morning.

17:50.192 --> 17:51.742
Ready?

17:51.810 --> 17:53.277
I don't know. It's super-steep.

17:53.328 --> 17:56.163
In fact, it's the steepest
accessibility ramp in Lima.

17:56.248 --> 17:58.449
I know.
I've conquered them all.

17:58.500 --> 18:00.701
I think I'm just gonna go
to the front of the school.

18:00.786 --> 18:03.170
That ramp is nice and gentle.

18:03.255 --> 18:04.422
Quinn Fabray!

18:06.174 --> 18:08.209
I believe in you.

18:12.664 --> 18:14.098
Now come on.
(sighs)

18:14.165 --> 18:16.550
Prove me right.
You can do this.

18:16.635 --> 18:18.719
I'm not gonna make it.

18:18.804 --> 18:19.553
You will!

18:19.638 --> 18:21.105
(grunting)

18:21.172 --> 18:23.307
My arms...

18:23.358 --> 18:24.725
...are like iron! Come on!

18:24.810 --> 18:26.110
You can do it!

18:26.177 --> 18:27.311
...aren't strong like yours.

18:27.362 --> 18:28.646
Yes, you are.
Lean forward and push.

18:28.697 --> 18:30.731
(laughs)

18:30.816 --> 18:32.450
(grunting): Ow.

18:32.517 --> 18:33.984
Come on. You're halfway there.

18:34.035 --> 18:37.238
You've got this!
Push! Push!

18:37.322 --> 18:39.523
That sounds familiar.

18:39.574 --> 18:40.658
(both laugh)

18:40.709 --> 18:42.493
It's just like
having a baby. Come on.

18:42.544 --> 18:44.378
You wouldn't know!

18:44.463 --> 18:45.529
Three,

18:45.580 --> 18:47.665
BOTH:
Two...

18:47.716 --> 18:49.800
one... zero.

18:49.868 --> 18:51.802
You made it!
Whoo!

18:51.870 --> 18:52.887
Oh, my God.

18:52.971 --> 18:54.672
Whoo!

18:54.723 --> 18:56.590
(both laughing)

18:58.143 --> 18:59.560
Now just stay
up there.

18:59.644 --> 19:01.812
I would say that was one

19:01.880 --> 19:03.647
of the hardest
things I've ever done.

19:03.715 --> 19:05.215
Until you go
to Six Flags.

19:05.267 --> 19:06.884
Look, I'm not trying
to be a buzzkill,

19:06.935 --> 19:08.235
but going to an
amusement park

19:08.320 --> 19:09.603
when you're in
a wheelchair--

19:09.688 --> 19:11.105
especially if you're
still getting used to it--

19:11.189 --> 19:12.439
can kind of
be a drag.

19:12.524 --> 19:15.075
Artie, it's Senior Ditch Day.

19:15.160 --> 19:17.828
It's the only Senior Ditch Day
I'm ever going to have.

19:17.896 --> 19:20.331
I completely agree,
which is why I want you to come

19:20.398 --> 19:21.332
with me on Friday.

19:21.399 --> 19:22.783
I promise you,

19:22.868 --> 19:25.419
it will be the most amazing,
incredible and inspiring

19:25.504 --> 19:27.087
Ditch Day ever.

19:27.172 --> 19:28.172
(bell ringing)

19:28.239 --> 19:30.073
Whoo!

19:30.125 --> 19:33.511
Welcome, guys, to the Cooper
Anderson Acting Master class.

19:33.578 --> 19:34.912
Thank you. Yes.

19:34.963 --> 19:37.431
Buckle your seat belts, kids,
buckle your seat belts

19:37.516 --> 19:40.584
'cause I'm about
to pour you a tall glass of

19:40.635 --> 19:41.886
"This is how it is."

19:41.937 --> 19:43.437
First thing you're gonna
want to know:

19:43.522 --> 19:46.023
Don't go to college.
It is a waste of time.

19:46.090 --> 19:47.141
Number two:

19:47.225 --> 19:48.976
Don't go to New York.

19:49.060 --> 19:51.478
Theater is lame
and Broadway is dead.

19:51.563 --> 19:53.113
Real actors do TV and film,

19:53.198 --> 19:55.449
which means Hollywood
is where it's at.

19:55.534 --> 19:57.568
Now let's talk headshots.

19:57.619 --> 20:00.738
Always, without fail,
turn into a pose.

20:00.789 --> 20:02.289
Again.
CLASS: Wow.

20:02.374 --> 20:03.624
And again.
CLASS: Ooh...

20:03.708 --> 20:05.576
And one more time.
CLASS: Oh, yeah!

20:05.627 --> 20:07.878
Yes, that is a dynamic headshot,
and bam,

20:07.946 --> 20:10.247
you just got your first
callback. So now you've got

20:10.298 --> 20:12.333
your "sides."
Your foot's in the door.

20:12.417 --> 20:14.284
What do you do next?
Gotta figure out,

20:14.336 --> 20:16.220
is it comedic or is it dramatic?

20:16.287 --> 20:18.005
Often, it's hard to tell, right?

20:18.089 --> 20:20.123
So do what I do:
ask the director.

20:20.175 --> 20:21.642
"Is this scene comedic
or dramatic?"

20:21.726 --> 20:23.761
He will know you're an
actor who's not afraid

20:23.812 --> 20:25.262
to ask the tough questions,
right?

20:25.313 --> 20:26.847
Why are you writing this down?

20:26.932 --> 20:28.265
Okay, what's the key
to a dramatic scene?

20:28.316 --> 20:29.433
Finding the emotion.

20:29.484 --> 20:31.185
Connecting
with your scene partner.

20:31.269 --> 20:33.020
Oh, no, no and no.

20:33.104 --> 20:35.356
The key to a dramatic scene
is pointing.

20:35.440 --> 20:37.324
When people are
really emotional,

20:37.409 --> 20:40.160
they point their fingers a lot.

20:40.245 --> 20:41.862
That's not true
at all.

20:41.947 --> 20:43.313
That's... that's
terrible advice.

20:43.365 --> 20:46.083
Excuse me, guys, I'm sorry.
I'm sorry, Blaine.

20:46.150 --> 20:47.835
Are you an internationally
beloved spokesman

20:47.919 --> 20:50.537
for the Internet's fastest-
growing credit score Web site?

20:50.622 --> 20:51.872
GIRL: No.

20:51.957 --> 20:53.657
I didn't think so.

20:53.708 --> 20:55.826
So let's focus in, okay?
I'm here for you.

20:55.877 --> 20:57.428
I don't normally do this,

20:57.495 --> 20:59.513
but because you're in brother's
class and you guys are so nice,

20:59.598 --> 21:01.131
I'm gonna give you some
Level II stuff.

21:01.182 --> 21:04.101
(excited chatter)

21:09.007 --> 21:10.941
The secret to great acting,

21:11.009 --> 21:12.576
<i>great acting:</i>

21:12.644 --> 21:16.530
ignoring whatever
the other actor is doing.

21:16.615 --> 21:20.234
Eye contact with a scene partner
is incredibly distracting.

21:20.318 --> 21:21.952
I try to tune them out entirely.

21:22.020 --> 21:23.203
Sometimes I wear earplugs.

21:23.288 --> 21:25.039
That way, I don't get distracted
by what

21:25.123 --> 21:29.860
they're doing, and I can focus
on the awesome acting choices

21:29.911 --> 21:31.194
I've planned ahead of time.

21:31.246 --> 21:32.830
Like eating
a roast beef sandwich, right?

21:32.881 --> 21:35.532
Other choices I can plan
ahead of time:

21:35.583 --> 21:36.834
screaming all my lines!

21:36.885 --> 21:39.036
Because I'm really intense.

21:39.087 --> 21:40.871
And the things
I'm feeling are really intense!

21:40.922 --> 21:42.172
Because I'm an intense actor!

21:42.223 --> 21:43.057
(laughter)

21:43.141 --> 21:45.709
Nicholas Cage, right?!

21:45.760 --> 21:48.378
Yeah, yeah!
Whoo!

21:49.547 --> 21:50.213
Bravo.

21:51.983 --> 21:54.485
All right, guys, I don't want
you to go cray-cray,

21:54.552 --> 21:58.221
but I brought in "sides--"
industry term--

21:58.273 --> 22:01.025
from a little show that
I auditioned for last week...

22:01.076 --> 22:02.392
<i>called NCIS.</i>

22:02.444 --> 22:03.610
What does that stand for?
(students murmuring)

22:03.695 --> 22:05.162
Oh, my nana loves that show!

22:06.898 --> 22:10.451
Now in this scene, Agent Sciuto
has just discovered a dead body.

22:10.535 --> 22:12.235
Who knows what will unfold?

22:12.287 --> 22:13.537
Don't look at each other.
Action.

22:13.588 --> 22:14.738
Here's what we know.

22:14.806 --> 22:16.206
Sergeant Pembroke
took a bullet

22:16.257 --> 22:17.424
at point-blank range.
What we don't know

22:17.509 --> 22:19.043
is why he's wearing a dress.

22:19.094 --> 22:20.511
There's a rumor that Sergeant
Pembroke was a transvestite.

22:20.578 --> 22:21.912
No, Blaine, say
the line again,

22:21.963 --> 22:23.297
but this time,
point your finger.

22:23.381 --> 22:24.915
Things are serious; a
man in a dress is dead.

22:24.966 --> 22:26.100
I don't really
feel like pointing, Coop.

22:26.184 --> 22:27.718
Just feels a little stupid.

22:27.769 --> 22:29.753
Well, when a choice feels wrong,
it's actually a good sign.

22:29.804 --> 22:31.188
It means you're right
on the edge, man.

22:31.255 --> 22:33.023
See, I don't know about that.
I feel like when a choice...

22:33.091 --> 22:34.441
(both arguing)

22:34.526 --> 22:36.193
Coop, you're my brother!

22:36.260 --> 22:38.562
Can't you just support me?

22:40.115 --> 22:42.733
I'm sorry, are you
talking to me right now?

22:42.784 --> 22:44.451
Because I can't tell
if you're talking to me

22:44.536 --> 22:46.453
if you don't
point your finger.

22:46.538 --> 22:47.871
Right?
(students murmuring agreement)

22:47.939 --> 22:50.124
That is lesson number one,
guys, right?

22:50.208 --> 22:51.575
Scene. Scene. Scene.

22:51.626 --> 22:52.659
Good work, buddy.

22:52.744 --> 22:53.744
We'll get 'em
next time.

22:53.795 --> 22:55.329
Let's go! Whoo!
Let's move on

22:55.413 --> 22:57.965
to a little acting exercise
that I like to call

22:58.049 --> 22:59.800
The Emotion Tornado.

22:59.884 --> 23:01.218
Get your hands
up to the sky...

23:02.670 --> 23:04.755
Just a busted control
panel, Mrs. Tennison.

23:04.806 --> 23:05.806
Nothing too serious.

23:05.890 --> 23:07.124
You're a lifesaver.

23:07.175 --> 23:08.291
Noah told me
you're going

23:08.343 --> 23:09.343
into business together.

23:09.427 --> 23:11.678
No, I said we were
thinking about it.

23:11.763 --> 23:12.930
Well, I think it's a great idea.

23:12.981 --> 23:14.131
And if you need any investors,

23:14.182 --> 23:16.016
I'd love to be a
silent partner.

23:16.101 --> 23:17.968
Or a noisy one.

23:22.757 --> 23:24.875
In California,
she's considered ugly.

23:27.078 --> 23:29.847
Dude, I'm not going to L.A.

23:29.914 --> 23:31.215
Okay, end of discussion.

23:31.266 --> 23:33.383
Let me just say this,
and I'll shut up forever.

23:33.435 --> 23:35.018
If getting hitched
is a team effort,

23:35.086 --> 23:36.419
why are you the one that's
always giving up everything?

23:36.471 --> 23:37.587
Maybe it's time
for Rachel to start

23:37.639 --> 23:38.605
thinking about you
for a change.

23:38.690 --> 23:39.923
It's not like
you're asking her

23:39.974 --> 23:41.191
to sacrifice her career.

23:41.259 --> 23:42.476
You heard Blaine's
famous brother.

23:42.560 --> 23:44.228
L.A. is where it's at.

23:44.279 --> 23:45.428
Rachel could probably
get on TV,

23:45.480 --> 23:46.763
play the quirky
next-door girl or whatever.

23:46.815 --> 23:48.482
And you could
try acting, too.

23:48.566 --> 23:50.951
Or go to college.
This could be your day job.

23:51.035 --> 23:52.870
You spend so much time
thinking only about her.

23:52.937 --> 23:55.405
Take a couple seconds
and think about yourself.

23:58.015 --> 23:58.015
+

23:58.927 --> 24:00.094
I can barely focus.

24:00.178 --> 24:01.679
The thought of a boy
clinging to my insides

24:01.746 --> 24:03.264
is making me even more nauseous.

24:03.348 --> 24:05.549
